<handout xml:id="handout-section-6-1-dotproduct">
  <title>6.1 Dot Product, Length, and Orthogonality</title>

  <page xml:id="p-6-1-overview">
    <title>Overview</title>

    <objectives xml:id="obj-6-1-topics-goals">
      <title>Topics</title>
      <ul>
        <li>Dot product of vectors</li>
        <li>Magnitude of vectors and distances in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m></li>
        <li>Orthogonal vectors and complements</li>
        <li>Angles between vectors</li>
      </ul>
    </objectives>

    <objectives>
      <title>Goals</title>
      <ul>
        <li>
          Compute (a) dot products, (b) magnitudes, (c) distances in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>,
          and (d) angles between vectors.
        </li>
        <li>
          Apply theorems involving orthogonal complements, row/column space,
          and their relationships to linear systems.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </objectives>

      <p><em>Motivating Question</em></p>
      <p>
        For a matrix <m>A</m>, which vectors are orthogonal to all the rows of <m>A</m>?
        To the columns of <m>A</m>?
      </p>
   

    <p><nbsp/></p>

    <definition xml:id="def-dot-product">
      <title>Dot Product</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The <term>dot product</term> of two vectors <m>\vec u,\vec v\in\mathbb{R}^n</m> is:
        </p>
        <me>
          \vec u\cdot\vec v = \vec u^T\vec v = \begin{bmatrix} u_1 \amp u_2 \amp \cdots \amp u_n \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} v_1 \\ v_2 \\ \vdots \\ v_n \end{bmatrix} = u_1v_1+u_2v_2+\cdots+u_n v_n.
        </me>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <example xml:id="ex-6-1-dot-zero" workspace="true">
      <statement>
        <p>
          For what values of <m>k</m> is <m>\vec u\cdot\vec v=0</m>?
        </p>
        <me>
          \vec u=\begin{bmatrix}-1\\3\\k\\2\end{bmatrix},\qquad
          \vec v=\begin{bmatrix}4\\2\\1\\-3\end{bmatrix}.
        </me>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
            Note that <me>\vec u \cdot \vec v = -1(4) + 3(2) + k(1) + 2(-3) = -4 + 6 + k - 6 = k - 4</me>. It follows that <m>\vec u \cdot \vec v = 0</m> if and only if <m>k = 4</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p><nbsp/></p>
  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-6-1-properties">
    <title>Properties of the Dot Product</title>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-dot-identities">
      <title>Basic Identities of the Dot Product</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Let <m>\vec u,\vec v,\vec w\in\mathbb{R}^n</m> and <m>c\in\mathbb{R}</m>.</p>
        <ol>
          <li>(Symmetry) <m>\vec u\cdot\vec w = \vec w\cdot\vec u</m>.</li>
          <li>(Linearity) <m>(\vec v+\vec w)\cdot\vec u = \vec v\cdot\vec u + \vec w\cdot\vec u</m>.</li>
          <li>(Scalars) <m>(c\vec u)\cdot\vec w = c(\vec u\cdot\vec w) = \vec u \cdot (c\vec w)</m>.</li>
          <li>
            (Positivity) <m>\vec u\cdot\vec u\ge 0</m>, and it equals 0 if and only if <m>\vec u=\vec 0</m>.
          </li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <p><nbsp/></p>

    <definition xml:id="def-length">
      <title>Length (Magnitude)</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The <term>length</term>, or <term>magnitude</term>, of <m>\vec u\in\mathbb{R}^n</m> is
        </p>
        <me>
          \|\vec u\|=\sqrt{\vec u\cdot\vec u} = \sqrt{u_1^2+u_2^2+\cdots+u_n^2}.
        </me>
      </statement>
    </definition>


    <example xml:id="ex-6-1-length-op" workspace="true">
      <statement>
        <p>Compute <m>\lVert\overrightarrow{OP}\rVert</m> where <m>P=(1,3,2)</m>.</p>
        <image width="50%" xml:id="sec-6-1-ex-magnitude">
            <shortdescription>Sketch of the point (1,3,2) in 3-space.</shortdescription>
            <latex-image>
                 \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.0, axis/.style={->,black}, 
                    vector/.style={-stealth,DarkBlue,very thick}, 
                    vector guide/.style={dashed,gray}]

                    \coordinate (P) at (3,2,1);
                    \coordinate (O) at (0,0,0);

                    %draw axes
                    \draw[axis] (0,0,0) node[anchor=south east]{$O$} -- (4,0,0) node[anchor=north east]{$x_2$};
                    \draw[axis] (0,0,0) -- (0,2.4,0) node[anchor=east]{$x_3$};
                    \draw[axis] (0,0,0) -- (0,0,2) node[anchor=north]{$x_1$};
                    \draw[vector] (O) -- (P) node[anchor=north west]{$P(1,3,2)$};
                    \draw[vector guide] (3,0,1) -- (3,0,0) node[anchor=north]{$3$};
                    \draw[vector guide] (3,0,1) -- (0,0,1) node[anchor=east]{$1$};
                    \draw[vector guide] (3,2,1) -- (3,0,1);
                    \draw[vector guide] (3,2,1) -- (0,2,1);
                    \draw[vector guide] (3,2,1) -- (3,2,0);
                    \draw[vector guide] (3,2,0) -- (0,2,0);
                    \draw[vector guide] (0,2,0) -- (0,2,1);
                    \draw[vector guide] (0,2,1) -- (0,0,1);
                    \draw[vector guide] (3,2,0) -- (3,0,0);
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
        </image>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
            Note that <me>\overrightarrow{OP} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 3 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}</me>. It follows that <me>\|\overrightarrow{OP}\| = \sqrt{1^2 + 3^2 + 2^2} = \sqrt{14}</me>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p><nbsp/></p>

  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-6-1-example-sum-length">
    <title>Example: Length of a Sum</title>

    <example xml:id="ex-6-1-length-sum" workspace="true">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>\lVert\vec u\rVert=5</m>, <m>\lVert\vec v\rVert=\sqrt{3}</m>,
          and <m>\vec u\cdot\vec v=-1</m>. Compute <m>\lVert\vec u+\vec v\rVert</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
            Using <xref ref="def-length"/>, see that <me>\|\vec u + \vec v \| = \sqrt{(\vec u + \vec v)(\vec u + \vec v)} = \sqrt{(\vec u \cdot \vec u) + (\vec u \cdot \vec v) + (\vec v \cdot \vec u) + (\vec v \cdot \vec v)}</me>. Note that squaring both sides of the equation <m>\|\vec u \| = \sqrt{\vec u \cdot \vec u}</m> yields <m>\|\vec u\|^2 = \vec u \cdot \vec u</m>. Also, note that the dot product is commutative. Thus, we have that <me>\|\vec u + \vec v\| = \sqrt{\|\vec u\|^2 + 2\vec u \cdot \vec v + \|\vec v\|^2} = \sqrt{5^2 + 2(-1) + \sqrt{3}^2} = \sqrt{26}</me>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p><nbsp/></p>

    <p>
      For any vector <m>\vec v</m> and scalar <m>c</m>,
    </p>
    <me>
      \| c\vec v\| = \lvert c\rvert\|\vec v\|.
    </me>

    <definition xml:id="def-unit-vector">
      <title>Unit Vector</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A vector of length 1 is called a <term>unit vector</term>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>Examples of unit vectors:</p>
    <me>
      \vec e_1=\begin{bmatrix}1\\0\end{bmatrix},\quad
      \vec y=\frac{1}{\sqrt{5}}\begin{bmatrix}1\\2\end{bmatrix},\quad
      \vec v=\frac{1}{3}\begin{bmatrix}2\\1\\2\end{bmatrix}.
    </me>

    <p><nbsp/></p>

  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-6-1-distance">
    <title>Distance in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m></title>

    <definition xml:id="def-distance">
      <title>Distance</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For <m>\vec u,\vec v\in\mathbb{R}^n</m>, the <term>distance</term> between them is
        </p>
        <me>
          \operatorname{dist}(\vec u,\vec v)=\lVert\vec u-\vec v\rVert.
        </me>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <example xml:id="ex-6-1-distance" workspace="true">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Compute the distance between
          <m>\vec u=\begin{bmatrix}7\\1\end{bmatrix}</m> and
          <m>\vec v=\begin{bmatrix}3\\2\end{bmatrix}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
            Note that <me>\operatorname{dist}(\vec u, \vec v) = \|\vec u - \vec v\| = \left\|\begin{bmatrix} 4 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix}\right\| = \sqrt{4^2 + (-1)^2} = \sqrt{17}.</me>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p><nbsp/></p>

    <definition xml:id="def-orthogonal">
      <title>Orthogonal Vectors</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Two vectors <m>\vec u,\vec v</m> are <term>orthogonal</term> if
          <m>\vec u\cdot\vec v=0</m>.  
        </p>
        <p>
          This is equivalent to
        </p>
        <me>
          \| \vec u+\vec v\|^2
          = \|\vec u\|^2 + \|\vec v\|^2.
        </me>
      </statement>
        <solution>
        <p>
            Proof: The equivalent statement, known as the Pythagorean Theorem, is true since <me>\|\vec u + \vec v\|^2 = (\vec u + \vec v)(\vec u + \vec v) = \|\vec u\|^2 + \|\vec v\|^2 + 2\vec u \cdot \vec v = \|\vec u\|^2 + \|\vec v\|^2</me> since <m>\vec u \cdot \vec v = 0</m> because the vectors are orthogonal.
        </p>
        </solution>
    </definition>

    <p workspace="true">
      The zero vector is orthogonal to every vector in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>.
    </p>
  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-6-1-orthogonal-subspace">
    <title>Example: Orthogonal Subspace in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m></title>

    <example xml:id="ex-6-1-orth-subspace" workspace="0.5in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Sketch the set of all vectors orthogonal to
          <m>\vec v=\begin{bmatrix}3\\2\end{bmatrix}</m>.
        </p>
        <image width="50%" xml:id="sec-6-1-ex-vector">
            <shortdescription>Sketch of the vector v in coordinate plane.</shortdescription>
            <latex-image>
                \begin{tikzpicture}[yscale=.72,xscale=.75] 

                    \draw[gray](-4,-2) grid (4,4);  
                    \draw[->,thick]  (-4,0) -- (4,0) node[above]{$x_1$}; 
                    \draw[->,thick]  (0,-2) -- (0,4) node[above]{$x_2$}; 
                    \draw[->,DarkBlue,very thick] (0,0) -- (3,2) node[above] {$ \vec v$}; 

                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
        </image>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
            Let <m>\vec x = \begin{bmatrix} x_1 \\ x_2 \end{bmatrix}</m>. Note that <me> \vec v \cdot \vec x = 0 \quad \implies \quad 3x_1 + 2x_2 = 0</me>. Therefore, geometrically, we can describe the set of all vectors which are orthogonal to <m>\vec v</m> as the line <m>3x_1 + 2x_2 = 0</m>. Algebraically, the set of vectors which are orthogonal to <m>\vec v</m> is given by <me>\Nul(\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}) = \Span\left\{\begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ -3 \end{bmatrix}\right\}</me>. It is no coincidence that this set is a subspace. (See <xref ref="def-orth-complement"/>.)
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p><nbsp/></p>

    <definition xml:id="def-orth-complement">
      <title>Orthogonal Complement</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>W</m> is a subspace of <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>, a vector <m>\vec z</m>
          is <term>orthogonal</term> to <m>W</m> if <m>\vec z\cdot\vec w=0</m> for every <m>\vec w\in W</m>.
          The set of all such vectors is the <term>orthogonal complement</term>:
        </p>
        <me>
          W^\perp=\{\vec z\in\mathbb{R}^n:\vec z\cdot\vec w=0 \;\text{for all}\; \vec w\in W\}.
        </me>
        <p>
            The set <m>W^\perp</m> is also a subspace of <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>. We have that <me>\dim(W) + \dim(W^\perp) = n</me>. Furthermore, for any subspace <m>W</m>, we have that <m>\left(W^\perp\right)^\perp = W</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <example xml:id="ex-6-1-col-row-orth" workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>A=\begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 3\\ 2 \amp 6\end{bmatrix}</m>. Find <m>\Nul(A)^\perp</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
            NOte that <me>A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 3 \\ 2 \amp 6 \end{bmatrix} \sim \ begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 3 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</me>. It follows that <me>\Nul(A) = \Span\left\{\begin{bmatrix} -3 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}\right}</me>. Note that <m>\vec x = \begin{bmatrix} x_1 \\ x_2 \end{bmatrix} \in \Nul(A)^\perp</m> if and only if <m>\vec x</m> is orthogonal to every vector in <m>\Nul(A)</m>. Since every vector in <m>\Nul(A)</m> is a multiple of <m>\vec v = \begin{bmatrix} -3 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>, we have that <m>\vec x</m> is orthogonal to every vector of <m>\Nul(A)</m> as long as it is orthogonal to <m>\vec v</m>. Note that <me>\vec x \cdot \vec v = 0 \quad \implies \quad -3x_1 + x_2 = 0 </me>. It follows that <m>\vec x = t\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix}</m> for <m>t \in \mathbb{R}</m>. Thus, <me>\Nul(A)^\perp = \Span\left\{\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix}\right}</me>. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-6-1-plane-example">
    <title>Example: Plane Orthogonal to a Line in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m></title>

    <example xml:id="ex-6-1-line-plane" workspace="0.5in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>L</m> be the line spanned by <m>\vec v=\begin{bmatrix}1\\-1\\2\end{bmatrix}</m>.
          Since <m>L</m> is 1-dimensional, its orthogonal complement <m>L^\perp</m> is a plane.
          Find an equation for the plane <m>L^\perp</m>.
        </p>
        <image width="50%" xml:id="sec-6-1-ex-ortho-subspace">
            <shortdescription>Graph of a line L in 3-space passing through the origin and the point (1,-1,2).</shortdescription>
            <latex-image>
                \tdplotsetmaincoords{80}{100}
                \begin{tikzpicture}[
                scale=1.4,
                tdplot_main_coords,
                line/.style={DarkRed},
                vector/.style={-stealth,DarkBlue,very thick},
                vector guide/.style={dashed,gray}
                ]
                    \coordinate (P) at (2,-1,2);  
                    \coordinate (Q) at (2.4,-1.2,2.4);
                    \coordinate (R) at (-1.2,.6,-1.2);
                    \coordinate (O) at (0,0,0);
                    
                    % Draw Axes
                    \draw[thick,->] (O) -- (2.8,0,0) node[anchor=north east]{$x$};
                    \draw[thick,->] (0,-2,0) -- (0,2,0) node[anchor=north west]{$y$};
                    \draw[thick,->] (O) -- (0,0,2) node[anchor=south]{$z$};            
                    
                    % Draw Plane (assume instructor will annotate slide with OneNote)
        %            \filldraw[
        %                draw=DarkBlue,% color of edge
        %                fill=DarkBlue!20,% color of fill
        %                opacity=.6, % sets opacity of fill and of edges
        %            ]          
        %            (-1,-1,0)
        %            -- (1,1,0)
        %            -- (-1,1,0)
        %            -- (-3,-1,0)            
        %            -- cycle;
        
                    % Draw Vector and Line L
                    \draw[line]     (R) -- (Q) node[anchor=north east]{$L$};
                    \draw[vector]   (O) -- (P) node[anchor=north east]{$\vec v$};

                    % Draw vector guides
                    \draw[vector guide] (2,-1,0) -- (2,0,0) node[anchor= west]{$1$};      
                    \draw[vector guide] (2,-1,0) -- (0,-1,0) node[anchor=south west]{$-1$};      
                    \draw[vector guide] (2,-1,0) -- (2,-1,2);      
                    
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
        </image>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
            First, note that by <xref ref="def-orth-complement"/>, we have that <m>\dim(L^\perp) = 3 - \dim(L) = 2</m>. Thus, the space <m>L^\perp</m> really is a plane in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>. Let <m>\vec x = \begin{bmatrix} x_1 \\ x_2 \\ x_3 \end{bmatrix} \in \mathbb{R}^3</m>. Note that <me>\vec v \cdot \vec x = 0 \quad \implies \quad x_1 - x_2 + 2x_3 = 0</me>. Thus, we have that <me>L^\perp = \Nul\left(\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp -1 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}\right) = \Span\left\{\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix}\right\}</me>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p><nbsp/></p>

    <definition xml:id="def-row-space">
      <title>Row Space</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The <term>row space <m>\operatorname{Row}(A)</m></term> is the subspace spanned by the rows of a matrix <m>A</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>Facts:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><m>\dim(\operatorname{Row}(A))=\dim(\operatorname{Col}(A))</m>.</li>
      <li>A basis for <m>\operatorname{Row}(A)</m> is given by the pivot rows of <m>A</m>.</li>
      <li>In general, <m>\operatorname{Row}(A)</m> and <m>\operatorname{Col}(A)</m> are unrelated spaces.</li>
    </ul>

    <p workspace="0.5in"></p>
  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-6-1-rowA">
    <title>Row Space</title>

    <example xml:id="ex-6-1-null-row" workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Describe <m>\Nul(A) \subseteq \mathbb{R}^n</m> in terms of an orthogonal subspace.
        </p>

        <ol>
          <li>
            <m>\vec x\in\Nul(A)</m> if and only if <m>\underline{\hspace{2in}}</m>. 
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>A\vec x = \vec 0</m>
                </p>
          </answer>
        </li>
          
          <li>
            This means <m>\vec x</m> is <m>\underline{\hspace{2in}}</m> to each row of <m>A</m>.
            <answer>
                <p>
                    orthogonal
                </p>
          </answer>
          </li>
          
          <li>
            Therefore <m>\operatorname{Row}(A)</m> is <m>\underline{\hspace{3in}}</m> of <m>\Nul(A)</m>.
            <answer>
                <p>
                    the orthogonal complement
                </p>
          </answer>
          </li>
          
          <li>
            <m>\dim(\operatorname{Row}(A))+\dim(\Nul(A))=\underline{\hspace{1in}}</m>.
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>n</m>
                </p>
          </answer>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-four-subspaces">
      <title>The Four Subspaces</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For any <m>A\in\mathbb{R}^{m\times n}</m>:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><p><m>\Nul(A)</m> is the orthogonal complement of <m>\operatorname{Row}(A)</m>:</p> <me>\Row(A)^\perp = \Nul(A) \quad \text{and} \quad \Nul(A)^\perp = \Row(A)</me></li>
          <li><p><m>\Nul(A^T)</m> is the orthogonal complement of <m>\operatorname{Col}(A)</m>:</p> <me>\Col(A)^\perp = \Nul(A^T) \quad \text{and} \quad \Nul(A^T)^\perp = \Col(A)</me></li>
        </ul>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <p>
      This geometric structure is often shown using overlapping regions representing the four fundamental subspaces.
    </p>
    <image width ="55%" xml:id="four-subspace-thm">
        <shortdescription>Visual representation of the four subspaces from the Four Subspace Theorem</shortdescription>
        <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1]
        
                % boxes
                \filldraw[draw=DarkBlue!50,fill=DarkBlue!15] (0,0) -- (-1,1) -- (1,3) -- (2,2) -- cycle;
                \filldraw[draw=DarkBlue!50,fill=DarkBlue!15] (0,0) -- (1,-1) -- (0,-2) -- (-1,-1) -- cycle;
                
                \filldraw[draw=DarkGreen!50,fill=DarkGreen!15] (4,0) -- (2.5, 1.5) -- (3.5, 2.5) -- (5,1) -- cycle;
                \filldraw[draw=DarkGreen!50,fill=DarkGreen!15] (4,0) -- (5.5,-1.5) -- (4.5,-2.5) -- (3,-1) -- cycle;
                
                % text labels
                \draw (0.5, 1.7) node[below]{Row$(A)$};
                \draw (0.0,-0.7) node[below]{Nul$(A)$};
                \draw (4.0, 1.1) node[below]{Col$(A)$};
                \draw (4.2, -0.8) node[below]{Nul$(A^T)$};
                \draw (-1.0,0.5) node[below]{\Large $\color{DarkBlue} \mathbb R^n$};
                \draw ( 5.0,0.5) node[below]{\Large $\color{DarkGreen} \mathbb R^m$};  

            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
    </image>

    <p workspace="1in"><nbsp/></p>
  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-6-1-angles">
    <title>Angles Between Vectors</title>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-angle">
      <title>Dot Product and Angle</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The dot product satisfies
        </p>
        <me>
          \vec a\cdot\vec b=\lVert\vec a\rVert\,\lVert\vec b\rVert\cos\theta.
        </me>
        <p>
          Thus, if <m>\vec a\cdot\vec b=0</m>, then either one vector is the zero vector or the vectors are orthogonal.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Proof: We will prove this theorem for vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m>. A similar argument can be made for two vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> by considering them in the plane (or line) which they span.
        </p>
        <p>
          First, note that if either <m>\vec a = \vec 0</m> or <m>\vec b = \vec 0</m>, then the equation is true since both the left side and right side are 0. Now suppose <m>\vec a \neq \vec 0</m> and <m>\vec b \neq \vec 0</m>. Then, we know that <m>\|\vec a\| \neq 0</m> and <m>\|\vec b\| \neq 0</m>. Let's consider the <em>unit</em> vectors <m>\vec u_1 = \frac{\vec a}{\|\vec a\|}</m> and <m>\vec u_2 = \frac{\vec b}{\|\vec b\|}</m>. Since both <m>\vec u_1</m> and <m>\vec u_2</m> are unit vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m>, they both lie on the unit circle. Note that rotating both vectors by the same angle will <em>not</em> change the angle between them. So, let's rotate the vectors so that <m>\vec u_1</m> lies on the positive <m>x</m>-axis. (This is similar to choosing a new reference frame in physics). Then, <m>\vec u_1 = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>\vec u_2 = \begin{bmatrix} \cos \theta \\ \sin \theta \end{bmatrix}</m>, where <m>\theta</m> is the angle between <m>\vec u_1</m> and <m>\vec u_2</m>. In this reference frame, we have that <me>\vec u_1 \cdot \vec u_2 = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} \cdot \begin{bmatrix} \cos \theta \\ \sin \theta \end{bmatrix} = \cos\theta</me>. By replacing <m>\vec u_1</m> and <m>\vec u_2</m> with their definitions in terms of <m>\vec a</m> and <m>\vec b</m>, we see that <me>\dfrac{\vec a}{\|\vec a\|} \cdot \dfrac{\vec b}{\|\vec b\|} = \cos \theta \quad \implies \quad \vec a \cdot \vec b = \|\vec a\|\|\vec b\|\cos \theta</me>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </theorem>


    <example xml:id="ex-6-1-angles" workspace="true">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the angle between <m>\vec v = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>\vec u = \begin{bmatrix} \dfrac{3 - 4\sqrt{3}}{10} \\ \dfrac{4 + 3\sqrt{3}}{10} \end{bmatrix}</m>. Note that <m>\vec u</m> is a unit vector.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
            Note that <md> <mrow>\vec v \cdot \vec u \amp = 3\left(\dfrac{3 - 4\sqrt{3}}{10}\right) + 4\left(\dfrac{4 + 3\sqrt{3}}{10}\right)</mrow> <mrow> \amp = \dfrac{9 - 12\sqrt{3} + 16 + 12\sqrt{3}}{10}</mrow> <mrow> \amp = \dfrac{25}{10}</mrow> <mrow> \amp = \dfrac{5}{2}</mrow></md>. Also, note that <m>\|\vec v\| = \sqrt{3^2 + 4^2} = 5</m>. Since <m>\vec u</m> is a unit vector, we have that <m>\|\vec u \| = 1</m>. Therefore, we have <me>\cos(\theta) = \dfrac{\vec v \cdot \vec u}{\|\vec v\|\|\vec u\|} = \dfrac{\frac{5}{2}}{5} = \dfrac{1}{2},</me> so <me>\theta = \operatorname{cos}^{-1}\left(\frac{1}{2}\right) = \frac{\pi}{3} = 60^\circ</me>. Thus, there is a <m>60^\circ</m> angle between <m>\vec v</m> and <m>\vec u</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </page>

</handout>